First, we need to find the intersection of sets A and B, which is denoted by A ∩ B. The intersection of two sets contains all the elements that are common to both sets.

A = {1, 2, 3}
B = {2, 3, 4, 5}

A ∩ B = {2, 3}

Now, we need to find the Cartesian product of the intersection (A ∩ B) and set C. The Cartesian product of two sets is a set of all ordered pairs (a, b) where a is an element of the first set and b is an element of the second set.

C = {6, 7}

(A ∩ B) x C = {(2, 6), (2, 7), (3, 6), (3, 7)}

So, the Cartesian product of (A ∩ B) and C is {(2, 6), (2, 7), (3, 6), (3, 7)}.
